This paper deals with game theory and optimization in the context of congestion games, which are typically studied in the computer science subfield of algorithmic game theory (cs.GT). The paper also makes use of concepts from optimization and machine learning, such as primal-dual methods and social welfare functions, which are relevant to the subfields of optimization (cs.DS) and machine learning (cs.LG, cs.AI). Finally, the paper's focus on the worst-case price of anarchy and its extension to approximate equilibria suggests a connection to the subfield of multi-agent systems (cs.MA).
